# .dockerignore — repository-root ignore list for all service image builds.
#
# WHY this file exists:
#   1. Build speed & smaller context — every `docker build` (context = repo root) streams the
#      working tree to the Docker daemon. Excluding build output, IDE state, and node_modules
#      keeps that context small so builds start fast and layer caching stays effective. The
#      Dockerfiles restore and compile inside the SDK image, so host-side bin/ and obj/ are noise.
#   2. Keeping local config & secrets OUT of images — appsettings.Development.json, *.user files,
#      terraform state under infrastructure/, and any local secret files must never be baked into
#      a container layer (image layers are inspectable and shipped to a registry). Runtime config
#      comes from environment variables and Azure Key Vault, never from files copied at build time.

# --- Build output (regenerated inside the build image) ---
**/bin/
**/obj/
bin/
obj/

# --- Version control & CI metadata ---
.git/
.gitignore
.gitattributes
.github/

# --- IDE / editor state ---
.vs/
.vscode/
**/*.user
*.suo

# --- Node / tooling ---
**/node_modules

# --- Local application config & secrets (must come from env / Key Vault at runtime) ---
**/appsettings.Development.json
**/appsettings.*.Local.json
**/*.env
.env
*.pfx
*.key
*.pem
secrets.json
**/secrets.json

# --- Test output ---
**/TestResults

# --- Infrastructure-as-code (terraform state, plans — never needed in an app image) ---
infrastructure/

# --- Documentation (not needed at runtime) ---
docs/
*.md

# --- Postman / local dev collections ---
AntKart.postman_collection.json
AntKart.*.postman_environment.json
